          <blockquote class="pl-6 py-3 border-l-4 border-emerald-500 bg-emerald-50/50 text-slate-700 italic text-lg rounded-r-lg mb-10">
            "It's a working platform two storeys up. The shift has been on since morning and it has been raining heavily. The rain stopped in the afternoon, but the deck never dried. A mason shifts his weight to reach for a bag of cement and his boot slides half an inch on the wooden plank, without anti-skid texture under him. He catches the frame rail. Nobody saw it. Nobody logged it. It happens again the next week, on a different height, with a different worker who isn't as quick."
          </blockquote>

          <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-12 mb-6">Why This Isn't a Seasonal Inconvenience</h2>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">Construction in India doesn't stop for monsoon. EPC contracts carry penalty clauses tied to work incompletion, not weather. Labourers booked for a shift have to be used in that shift, whether it is raining or not. So they keep working on platforms that are wet for three monsoon months, not just for one rainy afternoon.</p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">Water on a worksite doesn't behave the way people assume. It doesn't just wash away and run off. On a flat deck, it pools. A platform that looks dry from a distance can be holding a thin film of water in the low points of a panel, and that's enough to turn a normal walk across into a hazard. And mud carried in on boots makes the surface worse, as the shift goes on.</p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">There are also other factors that make it more dangerous. Wooden planks, when exposed to water and mud, start developing a thin layer of algae. This isn’t always visible, but it makes the surface extremely slippery. And in some areas, there are small oil spills or drops from machinery that mix with water and act like a lubricant on the planks. Together, these conditions turn an already wet surface into something far more dangerous.</p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">Then there's the cost side. A lost-time injury brings a stopped worker, an incident report, a safety audit, and in some cases a client walking off site until corrective action is shown. None of that costs less than upgrading the decking would have. Anti-skid planks aren't an added expense layered onto a project. They're cheaper than the alternative, just paid for at a different point in the schedule.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-12 mb-6">What Actually Makes a Plank "Anti-Skid"</h2>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">The term gets used loosely, so it's worth being precise about what it means physically. A standard scaffold plank is flat mild steel, with a painted finish. That paint is smooth by design, because smooth paint looks clean and sells well. The problem is that smooth painted steel and water don't mix. Water sits on top of a flat painted surface, and a layer of water under a boot has nowhere to go. That's what a slip actually is: the boot can't push water out of the way to make contact with the steel bottom.</p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-10 leading-relaxed">Anti-skid decking solves this with geometry. A surface of raised anti-skid dimples breaks up that flat plane. The raised edges of each dimple cut through the water film and drain the water, down through the grooves or off to the sides of each raised dimple. The boot makes contact with the raised steel, not with a layer of water sitting between the boot and the deck.</p>

