          <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-12 mb-6">Galvanized vs Painted, the Corrosion Factor</h2>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">Paint and monsoon humidity have a short relationship. Chipping happens fast under repeated wetting, foot traffic, and the pieces of material being dragged across the deck. Once the paint goes, the bare steel underneath starts to rust, and rust doesn't stay at the surface. It works into the raised pattern that's supposed to allow water to flow away from your platform. A rusted anti-skid pattern fills in with corrosion product and loses its grip almost as a flat sheet does. You end up with the worst combination: a plank that still looks like an anti-skid product but performs like an oiled bench.</p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">Hot-dip galvanized finish doesn't have this failure mode. The zinc coating resists the corrosion that eats through paint, and it keeps the anti-skid dimple pattern functional for years longer under the same standing water and humidity. This isn't really a spec sheet comparison. It's a total cost question. A painted plank that needs replacing in two monsoon seasons costs more over time than a galvanized one that doesn't, even before you count the labour to swap it out mid-project or the risk exposure while it's degrading.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-12 mb-6">What the Law Actually Expects From a Site</h2>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">The Building and Other Construction Workers Act, 1996, along with its Central Rules from 1998, places a clear duty on the employer or contractor to provide safe means of access to any working place. Scaffolding decking is part of that means of access. This isn't a technicality buried in a schedule somewhere. It's a direct obligation tied to how workers get from one point on a structure to another.</p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">IS 3696-1 (1987), India's Safety Code for Scaffolds, goes further on the weather question specifically. It calls for inspection after storms and heavy rain, and for shutdown where conditions warrant it. That standard doesn't specify exactly what counts as anti-skid or corrosion-resistant decking, but site safety teams should account for the fact that a deck which has lost its grip pattern to rust, or that's pooling water, is failing the inspection criteria the code asks for. Framing anti-skid, galvanized decking as part of meeting that standard of care is more accurate than treating it as an optional upgrade sitting outside compliance. It's the thing that makes a post-storm inspection pass instead of flag.</p>
          
          <p class="text-sm text-slate-500 italic border-t border-slate-200 pt-4 mt-6 mb-10">None of this is legal advice, and it isn't a guarantee against liability if something goes wrong. It's a description of what the rules ask a site to account for, and decking choice is one of the more direct ways a site can answer that.</p>

          <!-- RESTORED CHECKLIST BOX -->
          <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6 sm:p-8 my-12 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-black text-slate-900 mb-6 uppercase tracking-tight">Monsoon Pre-Shift Checklist</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-4 text-sm sm:text-base">
